The one refinement I’d make

If I were optimizing the Pantheon now, I’d stop asking:

“What is the invariant?”

I’d ask one question first:

“What is the minimal set of independent operators from which this domain can be reconstructed?”

That’s a basis-vector question.

It’s the same idea used in linear algebra, physics, and computer architecture.

Every time you discover two operators that are really the same transformation in different clothes, you merge them.

Over time, the Pantheon doesn’t grow by accumulating entries—it shrinks by discovering deeper unifications.

To me, that’s the direction that most closely matches the trajectory we’ve been exploring: not a bigger encyclopedia, but a smaller, more universal kernel from which many domains can be regenerated.